Dissimilarity Temperature & Fishing Interactions for All Regions

Here we will finally link temperature and fishing to dissimilarity

This code is Script X for Kitchel et al. TITLE manuscript.

  • This project is a collaborative effort to describe changes in taxonomic composition of fish communities around the world–as sampled by bottom trawl surveys.

  • Code by Zoë J. Kitchel

Patterns appear to be very survey dependent, and there’s a lot of unexplained year to year variation. - Warmer survey regions are more highly differentiated in general (makes sense, higher diversity ) - However, when we include spp num and fishing, temp drops out as a strong predictor - As fishing pressure increases, dissimilarity decreases (more fishing = more homogenous) - As # species increases, dissimilarity increases (more species overall = more heterogenous) - From before, more species, more negative dissimilarity coefficient (more likely to be differentiating over time)
